<paragraph id="F1053680FFCBF547FF715F7F65B4F872" blockId="20.[151,1436,1845,1979]" pageId="20" pageNumber="171">
Comments: 
<bibRefCitation id="952B4B71FFCBF547FEC65F7F6587F886" author="Smith, F." box="[288,437,1845,1871]" pageId="20" pageNumber="171" pagination="357 - 373" refId="ref20215" refString="Smith, F. (1874) A revision of the genera Epicharis, Centris, Eulema, and Euglossa belonging to the family Apidae, section Scopulipedes. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 4, 13, 357 - 373. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222937408680879" type="journal article" year="1874">Smith (1874)</bibRefCitation>
mentioned erroneously the sex of the specimen(s) described. This species has been misidentified for a long time, considering it to be a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="36BA4D03FFCBF547FC725F1360FBF8BA" authority="Lepeletier, 1841" authorityName="Lepeletier" authorityYear="1841" box="[916,1225,1881,1907]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscata">
<emphasis id="C3CEEA92FFCBF547FC725F136795F8BA" box="[916,935,1881,1907]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="171">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="C3CEEA92FFCBF547FC535F136034F8BA" box="[949,1030,1881,1907]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="171">fuscata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="952B4B71FFCBF547FBE85F1360FBF8BA" author="Lepeletier, A. L. M." box="[1038,1225,1881,1907]" pageId="20" pageNumber="171" pagination="455 - 460" refId="ref18876" refString="Lepeletier, A. L. M. (1841) Histoire naturelle des insectes- Hymenopteres II. Librairie Encyclopedique de Roret, Paris, 680, 455 - 460." type="journal article" year="1841">Lepeletier, 1841</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. The 
<typeStatus id="2E018822FFCBF547FAEE5F13610AF8BA" box="[1288,1336,1881,1907]" pageId="20" pageNumber="171">type</typeStatus>
material of this latter species is housed at 
<collectionCode id="97ABAE45FFCBF547FDE85F37666CF85E" box="[526,606,1917,1943]" country="USA" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/3kvn-7rck" name="Princeton University" pageId="20" pageNumber="171">MNHP</collectionCode>
and its detailed study showed that both are valid species, in spite of their superficial similarity.
</paragraph>
